{"Id":"b51dac9e04dc42cb83b7733fd952ede1","Name":"Zhaozhou Bowl","Description":"Zhaozhou’s bowl washing and related passages across Wumenguan, Congrong lu, Biyan lu, and Zhaozhou yulu","Tags":["zhaozhou","bowl","koan"],"CreatedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:00+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","ParentCollectionId":null,"Passages":[{"Id":"726aa1efb36d4ad9a75ce2d385cbe643","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2005.xml","ZhText":"趙州洗鉢","EnText":"Zhaozhou Washes His Bowl Zhaozhou Washes His Bowl Because a monk asked Zhaozhou, \"I have just entered the monastery; I beg the Master for instruction.\" Zhou said, \"Have you eaten your gruel?\" The monk said, \"I have eaten my gruel.\" Zhou said, \"Go wash your bowl.\" That monk had an awakening. Wumen said: Zhaozhou opened his mouth and showed his gallbladder; he exposed his heart and liver. That monk heard the matter not truly, and called a bell a jar.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:10+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:38:16.4014611+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0293c26","ToLb":"0294a02","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Zhaozhou Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"430c8f479a3e492d917d18350e7b38da","SourceRelPath":"J/J24/J24nB137.xml","ZhText":"問：「如何是學人自己？」師云：「喫粥了也未？」","EnText":"Asked, What is the student's own self? The master said, Have you eaten your gruel yet? He said, I have eaten gruel. The master said, Go wash your bowl.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:20+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0365a22","ToLb":"0365a23","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Zhaozhou Gruel","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"f3131d26efde4b43a08df9f2bf0274a3","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2004.xml","ZhText":"第三十九則趙州洗鉢","EnText":"39 Zhaozhou Washes the Bowl Case Thirty-Nine: Zhaozhou Washes the Bowl Instruction to the assembly: When food comes, open your mouth; when sleep comes, close your eyes. At the place of washing your face, if you pick up your nose, and when putting on shoes, touch your heel, yet at that moment you miss the word-head, then carrying fire at night and searching elsewhere in the dark, how will you ever come into accord? Citation. A monk asked Zhaozhou, A student has just entered the monastery and asks for instruction. Zhou said, Have you eaten your gruel yet? The monk said, I have eaten. Zhou said, Go wash your bowl. The monastery grove is not bad for you either. Solid gold, uncut jade. Long accustomed to patch-robed monks. Not equal to the senior monk. Do not guess sideways. The master said: Fishing for a dragon with a straight hook is already not skillful. When the lacquer bucket is still three inches from the hook, it is already the boatman and Jiashan cutting it off. It is not that people today have no share in it; mostly they just greedily take the bait and swallow the hook. Look, Zhaozhou neither snapped the fishing rod nor overturned the boat; he sat at ease on the stone bridge, and when passing by the little footbridge, there were naturally those who came ashore and fell into his hands. In the original record, that monk is said to have awakened on this account. It can be said the thread on the rod-tip was yours to play with; without disturbing the clear waves, the meaning was naturally distinct. Zhaozhou, like Ren Gong, found success in front; now watch Tiantong beat the oar behind in the verse: After the gruel, he orders him to wash the bowl; suddenly the ground of mind accords of itself. Such a swift opening is hard to meet. Not only today. Now, you monastery guests stuffed full of meditation, say then, within this is there awakening As always, after eating porridge, wash your bowl and go. or not? One person passes on hearsay, ten thousand pass it on as fact. The master said: Lingyun saw peach blossoms and awakened to the Way, then presented a verse to Weishan. Shan said, One who enters from conditions will never retreat or lose it. Xuansha heard this and said, Truly right, very truly right. Yet I dare guarantee our elder brother has not fully penetrated. Lingyun heard and said, Has master fully penetrated or not? Sha said, Only thus is it so. Tiantong's verse praises this monk's awakening, the mind-ground mutually matching. This monk, newly entering the monastery, is called greatly awakened, greatly penetrated. You well-fed Chan guests of the monastery, tell me: is there awakening or no awakening? This is called a probing question. Xuedou said, Originally there is no fixed count of delusion and awakening as many as hemp; only Lingyun is allowed to be a master hand. Xuansha said not yet through, yet Xuedou alone approved him as a master hand. Xu Liu carrying a plank, each sees only one side. Tell me, in washing the bowl, did the monk awaken or not? Peace is originally brought by the general, but the general is not permitted to see the peace he brought.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Wansong Xingxiu","Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:30+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0253a20","ToLb":"0253b17","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Wansong Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"1429722cda4e437ea0bdbf2b14d8a72d","SourceRelPath":"J/J24/J24nB137.xml","ZhText":"師上堂云：「兄弟！莫久立…」","EnText":"The Master ascended the hall and said: Brothers, do not stand long. If there is business, discuss it; if there is none, go sit beneath your robe and bowl and investigate thoroughly. When this old monk traveled, aside from the two meal times, which were places for mixed use of effort, all the rest had no other place to apply mind. If it is not like this, leaving home is far indeed.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:40+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:36:39.0220332+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0358c06","ToLb":"0358c08","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Zhaozhou: Robe and Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"bcf8c596384946d7aca0ea54daa9a97b","SourceRelPath":"J/J24/J24nB137.xml","ZhText":"平旦寅，荒村破院…","EnText":"At dawn, the Yin hour, this ruined monastery in a desolate village is hard to speak of. For the morning gruel there is not a grain of rice, only facing empty windows and dust in the cracks. Only sparrows chatter, no one draws near; sitting alone, I often hear falling leaves. Who says that leaving home","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Zhaozhou Congshen"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:45:50+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0371a04","ToLb":"0371a05","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Zhaozhou: No Gruel","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"987019bf169746d992afe2c39f72955e","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2004.xml","ZhText":"近代長蘆了和尚。天童同參…","EnText":"In recent times, Master Liao of Changlu was a fellow student with Tiantong and presided over seventeen hundred monks. Together with Zhu’an Gui, he opened the porridge and passed the summer, dividing quarters and entering the room. Xuefeng and Sansheng, though in different","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Wansong Xingxiu"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:46:00+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0249b28","ToLb":"0249b29","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Wansong: Gruel and Summer","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"7f872dfe338d4de8a069e2dd563692ef","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2005.xml","ZhText":"德山托鉢","EnText":"Deshan Carries His Bowl Deshan Carries His Bowl One day Deshan carried his bowl down from the hall. Seeing Xuefeng, Xuefeng asked, \"Old fellow, the bell has not yet been rung and the drum has not yet sounded-where are you carrying your bowl to?\" Deshan then returned to the abbot's quarters. Xuefeng brought it up to Yantou. Yantou said, \"Great Deshan has not yet understood the last phrase.\" Deshan heard of it and ordered the attendant to call Yantou in. He asked, \"You do not approve of this old monk?\" Yantou secretly revealed his meaning. Deshan then let it rest. The next day he ascended the seat, and indeed it was different from usual. Yantou went before the monks' hall, clapped his hands, and laughed loudly, saying, \"How glad I am the old fellow has understood the last phrase. Hereafter, people under heaven will have nothing they can do about him.\" Wumen said: As for the last phrase, Yantou and Deshan have both not even dreamed of it. When you check it out, it is like a shelf of puppets. The verse says: Recognize the first phrase then you understand the last phrase","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Deshan Xuanjian"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:46:10+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0294b28","ToLb":"0294c11","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Deshan Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"aa98ef51fc8a4ee7a66f9c361ce11a11","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2003.xml","ZhText":"舉僧問巴陵。如何是提婆宗","EnText":"Case 13: A monk asked Baling, What is the tradition of Deva- A white horse enters reed-flowers—what are you saying about marks and Baling said, Snow contained in a silver bowl.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Baling Haojian"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:46:20+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0153c20","ToLb":"0153c21","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Baling: Silver Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"9610485af2744c92a75300dc6d931719","SourceRelPath":"T/T48/T48n2004.xml","ZhText":"廓然無聖","EnText":"Vast emptiness, no holiness the incoming chance goes by a far road is it not like striking One time drinking water, one time choking A red face is not as good as straight speech at the nose while swinging the axe? In a master’s hands, a master is praised Missing, he does not turn his head after the pot falls vast and still, Let bygones be bygones coldly he sits at Shaolin. Old yet the mind does not rest Silently, silently, he fully upholds the true command autumn clear, still talking of military strategy the moon turns like a wheel of frost. Look with high-set eyes The river runs pale, the Dipper hangs low, the night-handle steady and exact robe and bowl Who dares take it on are entrusted to the descendants.","Notes":"","Tags":[],"MasterNames":["Wansong Xingxiu","Bodhidharma"],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T04:46:30+00:00","ModifiedUtc":null,"CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":"0228c14","ToLb":"0228c18","PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"Wansong: Empty Bowl","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":null,"Apparatus":null},{"Id":"2d19d0b93276489982dceb650d526c6a","SourceRelPath":"X/X59/X59n1069.xml","ZhText":"","EnText":"","Notes":"","Tags":["zh:釋迦牟尼如來拔除苦惱現大神變飛空大鉢法"],"MasterNames":[],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:01:53.4028554+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:36:05.6917769+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":null,"ToLb":null,"PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"This sounds funny","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":"Book","Apparatus":null},{"Id":"abb74750cf424e38be20299e54c72abf","SourceRelPath":"X/X59/X59n1098.xml","ZhText":"","EnText":"","Notes":"Somebody wrote an entire book about this?\r\n","Tags":["zh:衣鉢名義章"],"MasterNames":[],"AddedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:02:39.964888+00:00","ModifiedUtc":"2026-05-03T09:36:37.1386687+00:00","CreatedBy":"Fabulu","StartBlockNumber":null,"EndBlockNumber":null,"FromLb":null,"ToLb":null,"PreferredSide":0,"TranslationUser":null,"DoctrinalTopic":null,"LiteraryForm":null,"Lineage":null,"RhetoricalFunction":null,"LinkedTexts":[],"Summary":"This might be useful?","ReadingStatus":null,"SortIndex":null,"Importance":null,"AnnotationType":"Book","Apparatus":null}],"Links":[],"SchemaVersion":2,"Concepts":[{"Id":"5a290944b77449139d4e3369f5bbcb29","Name":"Bowl","Description":"Passages dealing in bowls","ColorHex":"#FF8A65","Tags":[],"Status":"Active","MergedIntoConceptId":null,"CreatedBy":null,"CreatedUtc":"2026-05-03T09